 (ii) locative name, occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Totehill</i> in 1251."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuthill","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of <b>Toothill</b>, primarily a Yorkshire habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (Yorkshire) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancashire), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwickshire), and Tothill (Lincolnshire). There are several further minor placenames of this type that may have contributed to the surname. Also occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Totta</i> (genitive <i>Tottan</i>) + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]},{"name":"Tootell","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tothill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Tutill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootal","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tott","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Tot(te)</i> (Old English  <i>Totta</i>,  <i>Tota</i>).  See also  Totty  ,   Tutt  , and compare Sabyna Tottedoghter’, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Kirkby Malham, WR Yorks); Radulphus Totusone, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Frisby on the Wreak, Leics). Some early bearers may belong with (2) or (3).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>tot(te)</i> ‘simpleton, fool’.","3  English: locative name from Middle English  <i>tot(e)</i> ‘lookout hill’ (Old English  <i>tōt(e)</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a lookout hill, or toponymic, for someone from a place so named, such as Toat Farm in Pulborough (Sussex) and Toat Hill in Slinfold (Sussex).  Compare  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tottle","meanings":["1  English:  see  Toothill  .","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name * <i>Totel</i> (Old English  <i>Tottel</i>)."]},{"name":"Tootill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootle","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tuthill  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":22,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":47,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine cause